Thanks for this, Josh. Now back in the US, Vermont specifically.

Yes, I hear you on not attempting to convert the other side, as it would =
offend. I think you nailed it further down in your email when you said =
that it=E2=80=99s going to be key to find Americans who perceive their =
views in a lighter way. We want them to be willing to see the other =
side, otherwise it=E2=80=99ll never work. Casting is going to be so =
crucial to this series. We=E2=80=99ll actually need a news producer. =
This is what their job involves often times, finding individuals that =
fit certain political and emotional profiles.

Reading further into your email, this is great: =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6that =
at a certain level there is a desire for unity. If we can give voice to =
that - if we can have each episode close with two people who were =
diametrically opposed demonstrating how they connected over something =
which previously made them act hatefully towards each other - then we're =
giving people hope.=E2=80=9D

Formatting notes below.

Reconciliation: I=E2=80=99ve thought about the reconciliation quite a =
bit, as an element of the program. The issue for me is dependency. We =
don=E2=80=99t want the show to be dependent on it because 1) it might =
not happen and 2) it might get too cheesy too quickly. I think this =
should attempt to remain emotionally non-partisan, as well as =
politically. Let=E2=80=99s all be adults about this and perceive of our =
intensity around these issues in a way that makes them less important, =
rather than more important. Meaning, reconciliation is dependent on the =
idea that what was being discussed is important, that views and opinions =
on divisive issues are important. But really, we=E2=80=99re trying to =
send the opposite idea.

Expert: Fair point regarding the partisanship of the =E2=80=9Cexpert." =
But if there was a historian, someone who can give us the backstory to =
the issue at hand, that might be helpful. We=E2=80=99ll need some sort =
of unbiased raw information, something that can=E2=80=99t be perceived =
of as questionable truths. Academics typically are great sources of =
nonpartisanship. But not always=E2=80=A6 Another option could be a =
=E2=80=9Ccorrespondent=E2=80=9D type role, someone who fills in the =
audience on the history of the program. I=E2=80=99ve seen a Chinese =
propaganda program <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marx_Got_It_Right> =
about Marxism that somewhat reminds me of what we=E2=80=99re talking =
about. I mean that strictly in terms of format, correspondents, etc. =
(That=E2=80=99s a dangerous sentence otherwise!)

Voting: Yes, the voting might be over the top. I agree, especially as it =
once again reinforces divisions.

Celebrities: This is a brilliant suggestion. But they=E2=80=99d have to =
be celebrities with no publicly facing opinions on the topics we choose. =
But I love this.

Highlighting funny interactions: There is a challenge here. On one hand, =
humor is a draw. But on the other hand, it=E2=80=99s divisive=E2=80=94at =
least, often times. There=E2=80=99s a deeper idea and challenge here =
regarding how to craft a nighttime program that doesn=E2=80=99t rely on =
negativity bias. I watch Trevor Noah because he is so ludicrously funny =
as it pertains to putting down those who don=E2=80=99t share my opinion. =
But how to craft an entertaining program that doesn=E2=80=99t rely on =
such things, one someone would want to watch after they get home from =
work, this is the challenge. As you said, we=E2=80=99re giving Americans =
a =E2=80=9Croadmap for healing=E2=80=9D (brilliantly put).

AI emails: Okay. This is it=E2=80=94this is how we can get content for =
the program itself. Yes, 100% onboard with this=E2=80=94if we can get it =
to work. Having the ability to ask and chat with the =E2=80=9CAI opinion =
swayer,=E2=80=9D will be a fascinating thing to generate hype about the =
program as well. It reminds me of John Oliver=E2=80=99s push to get =
folks to visit domains he=E2=80=99s purchased for each episode. But =
there is one centralized second screen experience, one site or one =
second functionality that people can focus around before, during and =
after the program. In some ways, this is like having an unlimited =
opportunity to speak intimately with the host of a program=E2=80=94but =
on a mass scale, anytime, anywhere.

Trevor Noah: Yes, 100%. This is an incredible opportunity to get this in =
his ear=E2=80=94and he is possible the person to speak to about such a =
show. I suspect we should get this all in order rather quickly then. =
When is the event?=20

Are you available to chat around these ideas sometime this week?=20

Thanks,
Matt



